    <!-- ══════════════ §6.4.4 SCREEN-BY-SCREEN ══════════════ -->
    <div class="dp-section" id="screens">
      <div class="dp-section-header">
        <div class="dp-section-num">§6.4.4</div>
        <h2>Screen-by-Screen Application</h2>
      </div>

      <h3>Splash Screen</h3>
      <p>
        The first thing an operator sees. Background must be <code>#0B1E2D</code>
        SovereignNavy — never white or system default. The version number is rendered in
        <code>#27AE60</code> MintSuccess to introduce the green accent from the very first
        frame. Application name in <code>#FFFFFF</code>; caption text in
        <code>#A0AAB4</code> TextSecondary.
      </p>

      <h3>Authentication Gateway (Login Dialog)</h3>
      <p>
        The "front door to the Mint." Three zones, each with a defined role:
      </p>
      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Zone</th><th>Treatment</th><th>Design Rationale</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Header</strong></td>
            <td>SlatePanel <code>#1C252C</code> with <code>2px #27AE60</code> bottom border. Logo centred, 80 × 80 px.</td>
            <td>Matches the menu bar authority inside the app — operator sees the same "institutional header" on login and inside.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Form Area</strong></td>
            <td>Radial gradient <code>#162E44 → #0B1E2D</code>. Inputs on <code>#141D26</code>, focused with <code>#1565C0</code> border.</td>
            <td>Premium depth without harsh contrast; the gradient centre draws the eye to the form.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Status Ribbon</strong></td>
            <td>SlatePanel <code>#1C252C</code>, TextSecondary labels, <code>#2A3640</code> separators.</td>
            <td>Mirrors the application status bar — the operator's eye never has to "leave" the palette.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table></div>

      <h3>Main Application Workspace</h3>
      <p>
        When the operator clicks "SECURE LOGIN," the transition must feel like a
        <em>curtain lifting</em>, not a jump to a new application. This is achieved by:
      </p>
      <ul style="margin:0 0 16px 24px;line-height:1.9;">
        <li>Menu bar background <code>#1C252C</code> — same as the login ribbon and header</li>
        <li>MDI workspace background <code>#0B1E2D</code> — same as the login form gradient edge</li>
        <li>Toolbar background <code>#1C252C</code> — continuous dark strip across the top</li>
        <li>Status bar background <code>#1C252C</code> — same as the login ribbon</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Tab Navigation (Issuance, Corridor Ops, Validation…)</h3>
      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>State</th><th>Style</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Active tab</strong></td>
            <td><code>#1565C0</code> fill · <code>#FFFFFF</code> bold text · <code>2px solid #27AE60</code> bottom accent border</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Inactive tab</strong></td>
            <td>Transparent · <code>#A0AAB4</code> TextSecondary text</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Hover (inactive)</strong></td>
            <td><code>#1C252C</code> SlatePanel lift · <code>#FFFFFF</code> text</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Tab bar strip</strong></td>
            <td><code>#0B1E2D</code> SovereignNavy — continuous with the MDI workspace</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Content pane</strong></td>
            <td><code>#FFFFFF</code> — high readability for forms and tables</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table></div>

      <div class="dp-callout dp-ok">
        <span class="dp-ci">✔</span>
        <div>
          The MintSuccess (<code>#27AE60</code>) bottom border on the active tab is the
          same green as the logo "Q" and the "Governance: Approved" badge. This creates a
          direct visual link: <em>the colour of access = the colour of value = the colour
          of approval.</em>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ══════════════ §6.4.5 QSS REFERENCE ══════════════ -->
    <div class="dp-section" id="qss">
      <div class="dp-section-header">
        <div class="dp-section-num">§6.4.5</div>
        <h2>Qt Style Sheet (QSS) Reference</h2>
      </div>

      <p>
        The global stylesheet is applied in <code>main.cpp</code> via
        <code>QApplication::setStyleSheet()</code> before any window is shown.
        Per-widget stylesheets in individual dialogs may override specific rules
        without conflict.
      </p>

      <h4>Global Structural Chrome (<code>main.cpp</code>)</h4>
      <div class="qss-block">
<span class="c">/* Main Window & MDI workspace */</span>
<span class="s">QMainWindow</span> { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#0B1E2D</span>; }
<span class="s">QMdiArea</span>    { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#0B1E2D</span>; <span class="p">border</span>: <span class="v">none</span>; }

<span class="c">/* Menu bar — SlatePanel authority strip */</span>
<span class="s">QMenuBar</span> { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#1C252C</span>; <span class="p">color</span>: <span class="h">#FFFFFF</span>; <span class="p">border-bottom</span>: <span class="v">1px solid</span> <span class="h">#2A3640</span>; }
<span class="s">QMenuBar::item:selected</span> { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#1565C0</span>; }

<span class="c">/* Drop-down menus */</span>
<span class="s">QMenu</span> { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#1C252C</span>; <span class="p">color</span>: <span class="h">#FFFFFF</span>; <span class="p">border</span>: <span class="v">1px solid</span> <span class="h">#2A3640</span>; }
<span class="s">QMenu::item:selected</span> { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#1565C0</span>; }
<span class="s">QMenu::separator</span>     { <span class="p">background</span>: <span class="h">#2A3640</span>; <span class="p">height</span>: <span class="v">1px</span>; <span class="p">margin</span>: <span class="v">3px 8px</span>; }

<span class="c">/* Toolbar */</span>
<span class="s">QToolBar</span> { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#1C252C</span>; <span class="p">border-bottom</span>: <span class="v">1px solid</span> <span class="h">#2A3640</span>; }
<span class="s">QToolBar QToolButton:hover</span> { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#1565C0</span>; <span class="p">color</span>: <span class="h">#FFFFFF</span>; }

<span class="c">/* Status bar */</span>
<span class="s">QStatusBar</span> { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#1C252C</span>; <span class="p">color</span>: <span class="h">#A0AAB4</span>; <span class="p">border-top</span>: <span class="v">1px solid</span> <span class="h">#2A3640</span>; }

<span class="c">/* Scroll bars */</span>
<span class="s">QScrollBar::handle:vertical</span>   { <span class="p">background</span>: <span class="h">#2A3640</span>; }
<span class="s">QScrollBar::handle:vertical:hover</span> { <span class="p">background</span>: <span class="h">#1565C0</span>; }
      </div>

      <h4 style="margin-top:24px;">Login Dialog (<code>logindialog.cpp</code>)</h4>
      <div class="qss-block">
<span class="c">/* Radial gradient background — premium depth */</span>
<span class="s">QDialog</span> {
  <span class="p">background</span>: <span class="v">qradialgradient(cx:0.5, cy:0.35, radius:0.75,</span>
               <span class="v">fx:0.5, fy:0.35,</span>
               <span class="v">stop:0</span> <span class="h">#162E44</span><span class="v">, stop:1</span> <span class="h">#0B1E2D</span><span class="v">)</span>;
}

<span class="c">/* Header — SlatePanel with MintSuccess bottom accent */</span>
<span class="c">/* background-color: #1C252C; border-bottom: 2px solid #27AE60; */</span>

<span class="c">/* Input fields — InputBg with ActionBlue focus border */</span>
<span class="s">QLineEdit, QComboBox</span> {
  <span class="p">background</span>: <span class="h">#141D26</span>; <span class="p">border</span>: <span class="v">1px solid</span> <span class="h">#2A3640</span>; <span class="p">color</span>: <span class="h">#FFFFFF</span>;
}
<span class="s">QLineEdit:focus, QComboBox:focus</span> { <span class="p">border-color</span>: <span class="h">#1565C0</span>; }

<span class="c">/* Primary button — solid ActionBlue (no gradient) */</span>
<span class="s">QPushButton</span> { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#1565C0</span>; <span class="p">color</span>: <span class="h">#FFFFFF</span>; <span class="p">border</span>: <span class="v">none</span>; }
<span class="s">QPushButton:hover</span>   { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#1976D2</span>; }
<span class="s">QPushButton:pressed</span> { <span class="p">background-color</span>: <span class="h">#0D47A1</span>; }

<span class="c">/* Status ribbon — SlatePanel mirrors menu bar */</span>
<span class="c">/* background-color: #1C252C; border-top: 1px solid #2A3640; */</span>
      </div>

      <h4 style="margin-top:24px;">Tab Widget (<code>scprojectpage.cpp</code>)</h4>
      <div class="qss-block">
<span class="s">QTabBar</span>           { <span class="p">background</span>: <span class="h">#0B1E2D</span>; }
<span class="s">QTabBar::tab</span>      { <span class="p">background</span>: <span class="v">transparent</span>; <span class="p">color</span>: <span class="h">#A0AAB4</span>; <span class="p">border-bottom</span>: <span class="v">2px solid transparent</span>; }
<span class="s">QTabBar::tab:selected</span> {
  <span class="p">background</span>: <span class="h">#1565C0</span>; <span class="p">color</span>: <span class="h">#FFFFFF</span>; <span class="p">font-weight</span>: <span class="v">bold</span>;
  <span class="p">border-bottom</span>: <span class="v">2px solid</span> <span class="h">#27AE60</span>;   <span class="c">/* MintSuccess accent */</span>
}
<span class="s">QTabBar::tab:hover:!selected</span> { <span class="p">background</span>: <span class="h">#1C252C</span>; <span class="p">color</span>: <span class="h">#FFFFFF</span>; }
<span class="s">QTabWidget::pane</span>  { <span class="p">background</span>: <span class="h">#FFFFFF</span>; <span class="p">border-top</span>: <span class="v">2px solid</span> <span class="h">#1565C0</span>; }
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ══════════════ §6.4.6 ENFORCEMENT RULES ══════════════ -->
    <div class="dp-section" id="rules">
      <div class="dp-section-header">
        <div class="dp-section-num">§6.4.6</div>
        <h2>Enforcement Rules</h2>
      </div>

      <p>
        To maintain operational trust and minimise cognitive fatigue, the following rules
        are mandatory for all current and future bearerCORE™ modules:
      </p>

      <div class="dp-table-wrap"><table class="dp-table">
        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Rule</th><th>Rationale</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>1</td>
            <td>All entry points (login, splash, license wizard) must use <code>#0B1E2D</code> as background — never white or system default.</td>
            <td>The Anchor Effect requires the operator to meet the same palette before they see any content.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>2</td>
            <td>The global QSS in <code>main.cpp</code> must not be removed or replaced with <code>setStyle("windows")</code>.</td>
            <td>The Windows style engine overrides custom QSS on structural widgets (menu bar, toolbar, scrollbars), breaking the palette.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>3</td>
            <td>Every primary action button must use <code>#1565C0</code> ActionBlue. Secondary / destructive actions use <code>#1A0808</code> with <code>#B71C1C</code> text.</td>
            <td>Colour encodes intent — operators must never have to read a button label to know if it is safe.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>4</td>
            <td><code>#27AE60</code> MintSuccess is reserved for success states, approval indicators, and active-tab accents only. Do not use it for informational labels.</td>
            <td>Semantic consistency — if MintSuccess appears, the operator knows something was approved or is currently active.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>5</td>
            <td>New dialogs and sub-windows must inherit from the global QSS. They may set per-widget overrides but must not introduce colours outside the palette.</td>
            <td>Prevents the gradual drift that fragments a unified system into a patchwork.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>6</td>
            <td>Critical alert panels (quarantine, lockdown, integrity failure) use <code>#1A0808</code> background with <code>#B71C1C</code> border and text. They must never use ActionBlue or MintSuccess.</td>
            <td>Red must retain exclusive ownership of the "danger" semantic. Colour-borrowing erodes the alert hierarchy.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table></div>

      <div class="dp-callout dp-ok" style="margin-top:24px;">
        <span class="dp-ci">📋</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Standard wording for technical specifications and procurement documents:</strong>
          <br><br>
          <em>"The bearerCORE™ platform utilises a unified 'Sovereign Navy' colour palette
          applied consistently across all session states, from the Authentication Gateway
          through the Issuance Desk. This standard is enforced via Qt Style Sheets applied
          at the QApplication level and must be maintained in all future modules to ensure
          operational trust, minimise cognitive load, and provide a single recognisable
          interface identity for central bank operators."</em>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div><%# .dp-main %>
